s with an overview of the instrument's early history, chapters on the clarinet in the opera orchestra and the traditional symphony orchestra, and examinations of important genres involving the clarinet (the concerto and the clarinet quintet). Also included are chapters on leading twentieth-century clarinetists, the instrument's use in the historically informed performance (HIP) movement, and an expansive look at the clarinet's use in ethnic traditions and early jazz. The emphasis on topics not covered elsewhere makes this book an important contribution to the clarinet literature. Written in an accessible style, this volume engages a wide range of readers, from professional musicians to clarinet aficionados and music lovers with less specialized knowledge.Contributors to this volume include Jane Ellsworth, Eric Hoeprich, Albert R. Rice, Ingrid Pearson, Julian Rushton, David Schneider, Marie Sumner Lott, Colin Lawson, and S. Frederick Starr.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aClarinetxHistory. 0aClarinet. 4aModern History. 4aMusic. 4aSocial History. 7aMUSIC / Musical Instruments / Woodwinds.2bisacsh  aClarinet.  aClassical Chamber Music.  aConcertos.  aEnsembles.  aGenres.  aHistorical Role.  aJazz.  aMusic Lovers.  aMusic.  aOpera.  aPerformer-Scholars.  aSymphony Orchestras.1 aEllsworth, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllsworth, Jane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHoeprich, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawson, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPearson, Ingrid E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPearson, Ingrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRice, Albert R